[{"id":30403,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["Hept-2-ene","Hept-1,3,5-triene","Heptane","Hept-2,4,6-triene"],"answer":2,"solution":"Compound (X) undergoes isomerization on heating with anhydrous $AlCl_3$ and HCl gas to give branched-chain alkanes. The formation of $2,4$-dimethylpentane (a $7$-carbon branched alkane) indicates that (X) is a $7$-carbon straight-chain alkane.<br><br>Aromatization of n-heptane at high temperature and pressure in the presence of oxides of V, Mo, or Cr supported over alumina gives toluene.<br><br>Cyclisation of n-heptane under similar conditions initially yields methylcyclohexane, which can further undergo dehydrogenation to form toluene.<br><br>Since all these reactions are characteristic of n-heptane, compound (X) is heptane.<br><br>Answer: Heptane","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (02 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30392,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["Haloform test","Lucas test","Silver mirror test","Benedict test"],"answer":0,"solution":"The optically active alkyl bromide $\\text{C}_4\\text{H}_9\\text{Br}$ is $2$-bromobutane, $\\text{CH}_3\\text{CH}(\\text{Br})\\text{CH}_2\\text{CH}_3$.<br><br>Reaction with ethanolic $\\text{KOH}$ undergoes dehydrohalogenation to form but-$2$-ene as the major product [A] (Zaitsev's rule).<br><br>But-$2$-ene [A] reacts with $\\text{Br}_2$ to form $2,3$-dibromobutane [B], $\\text{CH}_3\\text{CH}(\\text{Br})\\text{CH}(\\text{Br})\\text{CH}_3$.<br><br>Compound [B] undergoes double dehydrohalogenation with ethanolic $\\text{KOH}$ and $\\text{NaNH}_2$ to give but-$2$-yne [C], $\\text{CH}_3\\text{C}\\equiv\\text{CCH}_3$.<br><br>Hydration of but-$2$-yne [C] with $\\text{HgSO}_4$ and dilute $\\text{H}_2\\text{SO}_4$ yields butan-$2$-one [D], $\\text{CH}_3\\text{COCH}_2\\text{CH}_3$.<br><br>Since compound [D] is a methyl ketone, its functional group is confirmed by the haloform test.<br><br>Answer: Haloform test","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (06 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30476,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["B only","A only","C only","D only"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>The carbonyl compounds undergo Clemmenson&#39;s reduction in the presence of zinc amalgam and concentrated hydrochloric acid to form alkanes.&nbsp; The reagent in the Clemmenson&#39;s reduction effects the acid sensitive functional group. In the given reactant hydroxy group undergo dehydration to give alkene as shown below.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c87f71e0-afc7-42eb-8f2b-670c38c1d81f.png\" style=\"width: 509px; height: 88px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (11 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30550,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["(iv) &lt; (i) &lt;&nbsp;(ii) &lt;&nbsp;(iii)","(i) &lt; (ii) &lt;&nbsp;(iii) &lt;&nbsp;(iv)","(iv) &lt; (i) &lt;&nbsp;(iii) &lt;&nbsp;(ii)","(iv) &lt; (iii) &lt;&nbsp;(ii) &lt;&nbsp;(i)"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>For nucleophile substitution in aromatic halides</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a0c743fc-932b-4d1e-bc6c-41f12c8dce29-image.png\" style=\"width: 335px; height: 139px;\" /></p><p>Correct order is:</p><p>(i) &lt; (ii) &lt;&nbsp;(iii) &lt;&nbsp;(iv)</p><p>More No. of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> substituted aromatic halide, increase the rate of nucleophile substitution reaction in aromatic halides.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30612,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["One of the steps is endothermic in $\\mathrm{HCl}$ and $\\mathrm{HI}$","Both $\\mathrm{HCl}$ and $\\mathrm{HI}$ are strong acids","$\\mathrm{HCl}$ is oxidizing and the $\\mathrm{HI}$ is reducing","All the steps are exothermic is $\\mathrm{HCl}$ and $\\mathrm{HI}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"Anti-Markownikoff addition is possible only in case of $\\mathrm{HBr}$ and not in $\\mathrm{HCl}$ and $\\mathrm{HI}$. In $\\mathrm{HBr}$ both the chain initiation and propagation steps are exothermic, while in $\\mathrm{HCl}$, first step is exothermic, and second step is endothermic and in HI, no step is exothermic. Hence $\\mathrm{HCl}$ and $\\mathrm{HI}$ do not undergo anti-Markownikoff's addition.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (12 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30418,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"A cycloalkene (X) undergoes bromination with 1 mole of Br₂, consuming 2 moles of Br atoms (addition to the double bond).<br>The product (Y) has C:Br ratio of 3:1.<br>With 2 Br atoms present, the number of C atoms is 2 × 3 = 6.<br>Therefore, product Y has composition C₆H₁₂Br₂ with molar mass<br>$= 6(12) + 12(1) + 2(80) = 72 + 12 + 160 = 244$ g/mol.<br>Percentage of Br = (2 × 80 / 244) × 100 = (160 / 244) × 100<br>= 65.57%, which rounds to 66% (nearest integer).","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (22 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30581,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/efe0d851-198f-4c78-b949-308c2bbf5ad1-image.png\" style=\"width: 140px; height: 250px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f6340c34-60c5-48f0-a7a7-589f5965ca0b-image.png\" style=\"width: 153px; height: 240px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/498bcb06-bbfb-4eb0-b425-78a7d698bdda-image.png\" style=\"width: 135px; height: 196px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1bc97fef-1a7c-4c42-8886-4ea141913a32-image.png\" style=\"width: 224px; height: 188px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/196871b6-b38a-498d-a939-e362860e5dbc-image.png\" style=\"width: 758px; height: 510px;\" /></p><p>Free-radical polymerization (FRP) is a method of polymerization, by which a polymer forms by the successive addition of free-radical building blocks. Free radicals can be formed by a number of different mechanisms, usually involving separate initiator molecules.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30409,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["C, D & E Only","A, B & D Only","A, C & E Only","A & E Only"],"answer":2,"solution":"$Ph-CH=CH_2 \\xrightarrow[HBr]{(PhCOO)_2} Ph-CH_2-CH_2-Br$<br>Anti Markovnikov addition<br>• Reaction follow radical addition in presence of peroxide<br>• In absence of peroxide follow carbocation mechanism<br>• Benzene also formed<br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (28 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30543,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/206722f4-fbad-4039-8630-1767ffb9cded-image.png\" style=\"width: 108px; height: 83px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b3b2ab41-d6f9-48d4-a302-63ad81da7b7c-image.png\" style=\"width: 98px; height: 83px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5228e4d2-c1e7-4202-8c6c-c3706276a671-image.png\" style=\"width: 124px; height: 68px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c95196ec-d392-4993-ac17-527e5ccde6d4-image.png\" style=\"width: 119px; height: 81px;\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7159cdd1-ca17-44a7-856b-6e3666691912-image.png\" style=\"width: 253px; height: 116px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30424,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/kztyF0y_7NsozIn1rscFm0s3a5TMPnp6GgPTz0fbns8.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4Qro73NLgarESPekBFZ7IenVNRluX0IQ_wtmo41YsBg.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/U0PgGY8ue9PcrrT7xHsXAneQ_eKDgbeRk8sz660JCsQ.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/m2XOKtrME9nvKsATGuD2WvUj7et9J-XWNpklUYjJx6c.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/kqwjyv1BlQ9S2Dyoao4JpcDt1AXxx6PEJCa8E6mYXHA.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (4 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30553,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["Formation of anilinium ion","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> group is highly meta-directive","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> substitution always takes place at meta-position","low temperature"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f36c78f9-1c96-4d4d-960e-1d6041874178-image.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 194px;\" /></p><p>Aniline on protonation gives anilinium ion which is meta directing. So considerable amount of meta product is formed.</p><p>Direct nitration of aniline yields tarry oxidation products in addition to the nitro derivatives. Moreover, in the strongly acidic medium, aniline is protonated to form the anilinium ion which is meta directing. That is why besides the ortho and para derivatives, significant amount of meta derivative is also formed.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30498,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>CH</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>CH</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>CH</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo></math>&nbsp;Saytzeff products</p>","<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>CH</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>CH</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>CH</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo></math><br />Hafmann products</p>","<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>CH</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>CH</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CHCH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo></math><br />Hofmann products</p>","<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>CH</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>,</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>CH</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>CHCH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo></math><br />Saytzeff products</p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The Hofmann rule states that the major alkene product is the least substituted and least stable product when it comes to asymmetrical amines.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7a300eb1-c5e0-4262-8589-43153527d18b-image.png\" style=\"width: 451px; height: 140px;\" /></p><p>So, major product will be pent-1-ene and minor product will be pent-2-ene.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30460,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>An aqueous solution of sodium or potassium salt of carboxylic acid is electrolysed in this reaction, resulting in the dissociation of the salt into a carboxylate ion and sodium or potassium ions. </p><p>The total number of different alkanes are formed when the following mixture is subjected to electrolysis:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>COONa</mi><mfenced><mi>aq</mi></mfenced></msub><mo> </mo><mi>and</mi><mo> </mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><msub><mi>COONa</mi><mfenced><mi>aq</mi></mfenced></msub></math> </p><p>In this ethane, butane and propane are formed.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi>COONa</mi><mo>→</mo><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>∙</mo></mover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mi>COONa</mi><mo>→</mo><msub><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>∙</mo></mover><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><msub><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>∙</mo></mover><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mo>→</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>∙</mo></mover><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>→</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>∙</mo></mover><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>∙</mo></mover><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mo>→</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p>So, the total number of alkanes formed here will be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30609,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msubsup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo></mrow></msubsup></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msubsup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo></mrow></msubsup></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>+</mo></mrow></msup><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The reaction of propene with hypochlorous acid which is also the mixture of chlorine gas and water is an electrophilic addition reaction. It proceeds through the carbocation intermediate.</p><p>The whole reaction sequence is given below:</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/135070.png\" style=\"width: 192px; height: 180px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (03 Apr)","image":null},{"id":30628,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Zn_KMEhR_MXsv7dfpJhV2ejX5D9ElNJksYopHYD65kk.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/WHPOW8dlGdNY9mJReDXd3LGHF1lNbS8LlRcxP1y3YwU.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/axN2HZfVMPAYGYa6XMtr4vISY3jNXlenFixc3yEHwW8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/R0J05RdV6yzXj6xg1dnePpCkLv0iem089QKb1RjgYj8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":1,"solution":"$-\\mathrm{NO}_2$ is electron withdrawing which will destabilize $\\sigma$ - complex.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2008","image":null},{"id":30530,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/beeca9ad-4330-452c-b706-c977bc315f2a-image.png\" style=\"width: 227px; height: 103px;\" /></p><p>Numbers of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#963;</mi></math> bonds <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30483,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["hexa-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>5</mn></math>-triene","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>-methylcyclopenta-<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo></math>diene","cyclohexa<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></math>diene","cyclohexa<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></math>,<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo></math>diene"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>A hydrocarbon X with formula&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>8</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;uses two moles of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;on catalystic hydrogenation of its one mole. On ozonolysis,&nbsp; X yields two moles of methane dicarbaldehyde. The hydrocarbon is cyclohexa-1,4-diene.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/12f6ea3d-f3d6-4ab4-9b93-f1273bc8a560-9896324.PNG\" style=\"width: 430px; height: 100px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (31 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30617,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{LiAlH}_4$","$\\mathrm{Zn}-\\mathrm{Hg}$ with $\\mathrm{HCl}$","Glycol with $\\mathrm{KOH}$","$\\mathrm{H}_2$ with $\\mathrm{Pt}$ as catalyst"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1Uy8MtwNKUPe_bOZun2ceP84CttffQA-0rq-1V3JH50.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (22 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30452,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/VZjPcBqwdaPZGAy6aZtBpGw_GbHQxWEb8iSJjTi8qr0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/PVcv_5f0Dc3i6lgCx2ERkLrH9blFJFj9riSf2RJhVCE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/zkLG-XLYnsBI8d86J1jQCzmpcEj4pUjOeDiOm-4-0tk.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/w4DCXMxx4s85HALD5fwpXrIUP_Yl2hAkv0iailDEFnQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/k7cmXPY-khzs80ldVv6e8Lm3rOyk7KOPmt119ioh-tk.original.fullsize.png\"><br />$\\mathrm{A}$ and $\\mathrm{C}$ are position isomer.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30552,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/74bef9a0-18c9-4df6-bec5-38ad3ddd74a6-image.png\" style=\"width: 162px; height: 85px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e712a248-86b4-4b83-9fde-94074ed6f7a9-image.png\" style=\"width: 219px; height: 84px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/891ca8be-342a-49ec-b157-761612e684ec-image.png\" style=\"width: 219px; height: 86px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4db84133-eb8b-4556-999e-56241d3f2d97-image.png\" style=\"width: 219px; height: 89px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5a068873-b0c7-46e3-a7a6-f1533a75f468-image.png\" style=\"width: 463px; height: 568px;\" /></p><p>The final product formed is a derivative of&nbsp;phenolphthalein which has Pink color in basic medium.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30473,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a1a77efd-6043-409f-99a6-b127efc55638.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 167px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8024d477-7542-435c-b6cc-3c9ef514e4c6.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 92px;\" /></p>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>Cl</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Cl</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mi>Cl</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>When n-Hexane is heated with anhydrous&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HCl</mi></math>&nbsp;gas at&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>573</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">K</mi></math>&nbsp;under a pressure of about&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>30</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>35</mn><mi>atm</mi></math>&nbsp;it Isomerises to give a branched chain alkanes.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><munderover><mo>&#8594;</mo><munder><mi>HCl</mi><mo>&#9651;</mo></munder><mrow><mi>Anhy</mi><mo>.</mo><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mrow></munderover><munder><mrow><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CHCH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>methylpentane</mi></mrow></munder><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>methylpentane</mi></math></p><p>Major product in the above reaction is 2-methylpentane.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (13 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30478,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f99449af-de61-4743-af24-2ca801a3ff87.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 150px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5e20e890-5a57-4e78-a61d-b9e2aab14afe.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 168px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/729a2b45-9cbf-459e-b4ec-fe42cdd56a91.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 173px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fef86f7a-b489-4113-b2c4-f4c4d02545c0.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 161px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Alkaline potassium permanganate is a strong oxidising agent. In the given molecule alkene part undergo oxidation with&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>alk</mi><mo>.</mo><msub><mi>KMnO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>. The alkene part present in the given molecule is terminal alkene, hence it converts to carboxylic acid group and carbon dioxide. Finally, ester part in the molecule undergo hydrolysis in acidic water.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ae074ef6-4f7f-4292-bb47-28e8dcebb494.png\" style=\"width: 550px; height: 310px;\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (10 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30577,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/55de67e1-02d0-49d0-aa64-0030c5fb71c2-image.png\" style=\"width: 160px; height: 113px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9180d02a-aa0b-493f-8b43-f3ea35981546-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 76px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b1ab2e50-3762-488f-93e3-accb3f4e82d8-image.png\" style=\"width: 160px; height: 82px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/93928ad0-be72-4ceb-9af4-742310e61d9e-image.png\" style=\"width: 160px; height: 72px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>This reaction is the halohydration of alkene. It is an electrophilic addition reaction.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/61fb1145-f910-4446-bb82-e55aa173bf07-ef335eea-7a20-41d2-ac30-736362ebb571-image.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 62px;\" /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b9383e0f-b370-4281-b699-b62221f1f947-image48.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 227px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30616,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/gThXEaNogFuIoOaRO5q27DvaPrGlwo6LW9NF7U3E0Vc.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/EojC9Lr8jkzWyq-smlE7kB7WE9fNaNpRLt-qmxOTYTc.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/x7ZY35KI48s6cnXp2_re4rxYkUAT2xwdYruzAzCKxIQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/_6BCuKM51sL2ohKpDp7j3U9wQeFXk6x_XBGA-iyJEWo.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":2,"solution":"The major component of Borsch reagent is 2,4- dinitrophenyl hydrazine which can be obtained by reaction of 2,4-dinitrochloro benzene and hydrazine\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/RRG8qBuKpt1U3eB-Jwk7N1jUCKZByAfjwEe-TXAtbBI.original.fullsize.png\"><br><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/n-lxFT54f0PvQPDekDXp5G7QkLPI-8jeto7HfnBIb_c.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (22 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30496,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Nitration is an electrophilic aromatic substitution reaction. The <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>&nbsp;effect increases the rate of nitration whereas the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math>&nbsp;effect decreases the rate of nitration.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>(</mo><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi>Br</mi><mo>(</mo><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>but</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>dominant</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>(</mo><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mo>)</mo></math></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/416dfc6e-e7a4-4fcc-85d3-22a4ab1c5c88-image.png\" style=\"width: 456px; height: 150px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> is strongly deactivating</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi>Br</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo></math> deactivating</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo></math> activating group</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#60;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30537,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["Carbocation&nbsp;B&nbsp;is more stable and formed relatively at faster rate","Carbocation A is more stable and formed relatively at slow rate","Carbocation&nbsp;B&nbsp;is more stable and formed relatively at slow rate","Carbocation A is more stable and formed relatively at faster rate"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a63692ba-0d1d-4021-b901-2c15f7c092d7-image.png\" style=\"width: 424px; height: 150px;\" /></p><p>This is more stable due to secondary cation formation and formed with faster rate due to low activation energy.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30632,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c5j-2KslK95XGC4US9vpaIuWO_gpPa4LEiWtoUfU5JA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","$\\mathrm{CH}_2=\\mathrm{CH}_2$","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/HDTbTM1f2GjMSqnbw47IyHYEvhGWptrqjxLyl_a1cd8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/iFBno9Oq8OMggihotcGIQURIPeql98wDQ9PdNJAQ4fc.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":1,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2006","image":null},{"id":30475,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">A</mi></math> is true but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">R</mi></math> is false","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">A</mi></math> is false but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">R</mi></math> is true","Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">A</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">R</mi></math> are true and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">R</mi></math> is the correct explanation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">A</mi></math>","Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">A</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">R</mi></math> are true and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">R</mi></math> is NOT the correct explanation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">A</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>The reagent hydrazine in alkaline medium is used in the Wolff-Kishner reduction reaction. In this reaction aldehydes and ketone converts to respective alkanes.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/847d4718-67f2-4c71-b939-fc0b8f180e3c.png\" style=\"width: 252px; height: 83px;\" /></p><p>This reaction is not good for base sensitive groups in the carbonyl compounds.&nbsp; The following chloro carbonyl compound give alkene as elimination reaction expected in basic medium.</p><p>&nbsp;<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/92c6d5e7-53a9-4df2-a873-b0e5e11474db.png\" style=\"width: 343px; height: 93px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (11 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30531,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>PO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>Cl</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>PO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>PO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>CH</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi>Cl</mi></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi>PO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8f2082f2-52e4-4f1a-82e5-ba65b478519e-image.png\" style=\"width: 486px; height: 179px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (22 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30585,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/03334b10-8457-444b-9060-506954083074-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 160px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d42c5739-b01f-4c76-adb7-9784e8f084d7-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 141px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1c03e1dc-6fa6-4c52-b1ad-cb75a6bc4b2b-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 161px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/37b78dec-5fd5-46cf-b957-0f7a99a2fbd2-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 143px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In case of excess&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HBr</mi></math>, initially it will undergo&nbsp;electrophillic addition reaction and then it will attack on the methoxy group.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/89a80b4a-f2d3-450a-beb4-c48e0df3af4f-lpppa.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 183px;\" /></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0d545705-d82f-4ec0-9a3c-8852fae7f7e5-qwqq.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 182px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30596,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<p><img height=\"95\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/386d892f-f49e-431c-87a2-1a7cfd3eddd7-image.png\" width=\"107\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"67\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/14c6816d-8720-4e0d-882e-677723d58a7a-image.png\" width=\"189\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"100\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f069343e-c266-4026-b7c8-794a704a971b-image.png\" width=\"150\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"95\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/48af9c3f-ea2f-4146-bc84-587fbf3c034b-image.png\" width=\"130\" /></p>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7b84c563-766f-4c6e-bf5d-79d7084b94a0-2741b4ad-f9ef-4136-a20b-ee22c52e91c8-image.png\" style=\"width: 628px; height: 214px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (16 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30394,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["$0.42$","$0.82$","$0.62$","$0.12$"],"answer":3,"solution":"$2$-methylpropene reacts with dilute $H_2SO_4$ to undergo hydration, forming tert-butyl alcohol as the major product (X).<br><br>The reaction is:<br><br>$CH_2=C(CH_3)_2 \\xrightarrow{\\text{dil. } H_2SO_4} (CH_3)_3C-OH$<br><br>Product (X) is an alcohol, which is significantly more polar than the starting alkene due to the presence of the $-OH$ group. In normal phase chromatography, the stationary phase (such as silica gel) is highly polar. The polar $-OH$ group forms strong hydrogen bonds with the stationary phase, causing the alcohol to be adsorbed more strongly than the non-polar alkene.<br><br>Consequently, the alcohol travels a shorter distance along the chromatography plate, resulting in a lower $R_f$ value compared to the alkene.<br><br>Since the $R_f$ value of $2$-methylpropene is $0.42$, the $R_f$ value of product (X) must be less than $0.42$. Among the given choices, only $0.12$ satisfies this condition.<br><br>Answer: $0.12$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (06 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30590,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e1JCFelxI1KL0EwOS_cf1_q5b87Z2pbdBYkq16sRCrQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/oWt_j5ZHax73iFhTxycxd2u8hPB7QbZZsuQt9eqWAxw.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1Lv_Un2goLmcr-OzOptDObNTpjzBS6odpVjK04Wp8XM.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/JsvOZjy7FzcE6KoyE4rHK_FPpS5sHMXBuKOJEI2Jsq4.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/XmxXOJ2Dw2yggHqmJI6xOd051O01FNC62K_geQpJFRY.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30412,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["","","",""],"answer":3,"solution":"The vicinal dibromide undergoes elimination with $\\text{Zn}/\\Delta$ to form cyclohexene.<br><br>Cyclohexene reacts with HBr. The secondary carbocation formed undergoes a 1,2-hydride shift to give a more stable tertiary carbocation, which then combines with $\\text{Br}^-$ to give 1-bromocyclohexane (with Br at the more substituted position).<br><br>The major product (P) is 1-bromo-1-methylcyclohexane (tertiary alkyl bromide).","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (23 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30492,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Hydrocarbons","question":"","options":["Statement I is false but Statement II is true","Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Both Statement I and Statement II are true"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>The Clemmensen reduction is a reaction that is used to reduce aldehydes or ketones to alkanes using hydrochloric acid and zinc amalgam. In this reaction amide can undergo hydrolysis to convert into carboxylic acid.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/db2f7dc2-4686-45ba-a5f8-8557ebc197cc-image.png\" style=\"width: 464px; height: 86px;\" /></p><p>The Wolff&ndash;Kishner reduction is a reaction used in organic chemistry to convert carbonyl functionalities into methylene groups in the presence of hydrazine in basic medium. Due to the alkaline medium, alkyl halides undergo beta elimination to convert into alkene as shown below.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7281e158-681d-4565-a5af-4f9454704846-image.png\" style=\"width: 495px; height: 92px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (24 Jan Shift 2)","image":null}]